Using plain HTTP for API calls is extremely dangerous and exposes your application to man-in-the-middle attacks. Any sensitive data transmitted over HTTP can be intercepted, read, and modified by attackers on the network.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;
import java.io.OutputStream;
import java.net.HttpURLConnection;
import java.net.URL;
import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;

public class InsecureApiClient {

    private static final String API_ENDPOINT = "http://api.payment-service.com/process";

    public String processPayment(String cardNumber, String cvv, double amount) throws Exception {
        URL url = new URL(API_ENDPOINT);  // VULNERABLE: Using HTTP instead of HTTPS
        HttpURLConnection conn = (HttpURLConnection) url.openConnection();

        conn.setRequestMethod("POST");
        conn.setRequestProperty("Content-Type", "application/json");
        conn.setRequestProperty("Authorization", "Bearer sk_live_abc123xyz");  // Token sent in cleartext!
        conn.setDoOutput(true);

        // Sensitive payment data sent unencrypted
        String jsonPayload = String.format(
            "{\"card\":\"%s\",\"cvv\":\"%s\",\"amount\":%.2f}",
            cardNumber, cvv, amount
        );

        try (OutputStream os = conn.getOutputStream()) {
            byte[] input = jsonPayload.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
            os.write(input, 0, input.length);
        }

        StringBuilder response = new StringBuilder();
        try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(
                new InputStreamReader(conn.getInputStream(), StandardCharsets.UTF_8))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
                response.append(line);
            }
        }
        return response.toString();
    }
}
```

**Attack Scenario**:
```bash
# Attacker on same network using tcpdump or Wireshark
sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -A 'port 80 and host api.payment-service.com'

# Output shows cleartext data:
# POST /process HTTP/1.1
# Authorization: Bearer sk_live_abc123xyz
# {"card":"4111111111111111","cvv":"123","amount":999.99}
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- All data transmitted in cleartext, readable by anyone on the network path
- API keys and authentication tokens exposed to passive eavesdropping
- Credit card data (PCI-DSS violation) transmitted without encryption
- Attackers can modify requests/responses in transit (active MITM)
- No server identity verification - susceptible to DNS spoofing attacks

**SECURE VERSION**:

```java
import javax.net.ssl.HttpsURLConnection;
import javax.net.ssl.SSLContext;
