**Defense in Depth Layers**:

1. **State Parameter with Embedded Provider**:
```javascript
// Prevents IdP mixup attacks - provider is cryptographically bound to state
const payload = JSON.stringify({ r: random, t: timestamp, p: provider });
const signature = crypto.createHmac('sha256', secret).update(payload).digest('hex');
// Verification checks both state validity AND provider match
```

2. **PKCE for Public/Mobile Clients**:
```javascript
// Code verifier never leaves the client until token exchange
const codeVerifier = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('base64url');
const codeChallenge = crypto.createHash('sha256').update(codeVerifier).digest('base64url');
// Authorization code is useless without the verifier
```

3. **ID Token Validation (OpenID Connect)**:
```javascript
// Validates issuer, audience, nonce, and expiration
// Prevents token injection from different providers
if (!payload.iss.startsWith(config.issuer)) return null;
if (!aud.includes(config.clientId)) return null;
if (payload.nonce !== expectedNonce) return null;
```

**Additional Protections**:
- **Whitelist-only providers**: Enumerated providers prevent injection of malicious OAuth endpoints
- **Session regeneration**: Prevents session fixation after authentication completes
- **Comprehensive audit logging**: All OAuth events logged with IP, user agent, timestamps
- **Rate limiting**: 20 attempts per 15 minutes prevents brute force
- **Timeout on external requests**: 10-second timeout prevents hanging connections
- **Strict redirect URI**: Hardcoded, never from request parameters
- **Provider-specific handling**: GitHub's separate email API handled correctly
- **Redis session store**: Distributed sessions for horizontal scaling

Placing your admin panel at a predictable URL like `/admin` is extremely dangerous. Attackers actively scan for common admin paths and exploit weak authentication. This was a key factor in the 2022 Magento attacks (CVE-2022-24086) where exposed admin panels led to widespread compromise.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```php
<?php
// File: /admin/index.php - INSECURE ADMIN PANEL

session_start();

// Simple authentication with no protections
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $username = $_POST['username'];
    $password = $_POST['password'];

    // Hardcoded credentials - terrible practice
    if ($username === 'admin' && $password === 'admin123') {
        $_SESSION['admin_logged_in'] = true;
        $_SESSION['admin_user'] = $username;
        header('Location: dashboard.php');
        exit;
    } else {
        $error = "Invalid credentials";
    }
}
?>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head><title>Admin Login</title></head>
<body>
    <h1>Admin Panel</h1>
    <form method="POST">
        <input type="text" name="username" placeholder="Username">
        <input type="password" name="password" placeholder="Password">
        <button type="submit">Login</button>
    </form>
    <?php if (isset($error)) echo "<p style='color:red'>$error</p>"; ?>
</body>
</html>
```

**Attack Payload**:
```bash
# Attackers use automated tools to find admin panels
dirsearch -u https://target.com -w /usr/share/wordlists/admin-panels.txt

# Common paths scanned:
# /admin, /administrator, /admin.php, /adminpanel
# /manage, /backend, /control, /dashboard
# /wp-admin, /admin/login, /admin/index.php

# Then brute force with common credentials
hydra -l admin -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt https://target.com/admin http-post-form "/admin/index.php:username=^USER^&password=^PASS^:Invalid"
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Predictable URL makes admin panel easy to discover via automated scanning
- No rate limiting allows unlimited brute force attempts
- Hardcoded credentials are trivially discovered
- No IP whitelisting means anyone can attempt access
- No CSRF protection on login form
- No multi-factor authentication
- Session fixation vulnerability (session not regenerated on login)

**SECURE VERSION**:

